19:24.463 --> 19:26.132 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Congressman Tom
Marino, thank
you.

19:26.232 --> 19:26.799 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Daniel Garza, we thank you both.

19:26.899 --> 19:28.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DANIEL GARZA: Pleasure.

19:28.100 --> 19:30.503 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Thank you both very
much.

19:30.603 --> 19:35.608 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tonight, however, we continue
our series exploring
Donald Trump's life, his
transformation from

19:35.708 --> 19:41.080 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a borough kid in Queens to a
presidential
contender who has taken the
party by storm.

19:41.180 --> 19:46.652 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In this second installment, we
look at the
rise of the Trump brand, the
boom, the bankruptcies,

19:46.752 --> 19:52.324 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and his celebrity reemergence.

19:52.425 --> 19:57.797 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Long before his name became a
household one,
Donald Trump, fresh out of
business school,

19:57.897 --> 20:03.002 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
was already drawn to Manhattan's
flashiest
lights, those on the Great White
Way.

20:03.102 --> 20:07.506 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MICHAEL D'ANTONIO, Trump
Biographer: He was
always intrigued by performance,
and the very

20:07.606 --> 20:12.578 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
first business activity he
really got involved
with was the production of a
Broadway play.

20:12.678 --> 20:18.350 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
GWEN IFILL: That's author
Michael D'Antonio.
The play, which Trump backed in
1970, was

20:18.451 --> 20:23.889 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
"Paris Is Out." But the
theatrical venture
closed almost as quickly as it
opened, so

20:23.989 --> 20:25.758 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Trump retreated to his roots.

20:25.858 --> 20:30.896 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL D'ANTONIO: When he
eventually turned
toward the family business in
real estate

20:30.996 --> 20:38.037 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in the early 1970s, he was
determined to use
celebrity to help build the
business. And

20:38.137 --> 20:43.943 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think he understood that you
could be a
real estate developer in
Manhattan and also

20:44.043 --> 20:45.911 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
be famous.

20:46.011 --> 20:49.715 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Enter Donald Trump,
the builder:
cushioned against risk by his
father's wealth

20:49.815 --> 20:55.321 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and political connections, yet
still longing
for a piece of Manhattan
glamour.

20:55.421 --> 20:57.223 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Writer Gwenda Blair:

20:57.323 --> 21:00.960 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWENDA BLAIR, Author, "The
Trumps": When Donald
came to Manhattan in the
mid-'70s, New York

21:01.060 --> 21:06.665 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
City was in terrible financial
straits, on
the verge of bankruptcy. The
people who dealt

21:06.765 --> 21:13.205 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with him in those early days
said he just
jumped through the phone. He was
so competitive,

21:13.305 --> 21:20.045 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
so ambitious, so eager, that he
just jumped
into the spotlight. Every
possibility to get

21:20.146 --> 21:22.248 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
any kind of attention, he went
for it.

21:22.348 --> 21:27.486 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: His first major
project was the
old Commodore Hotel, a crumbling
eyesore in

21:27.586 --> 21:31.590 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the heart of the city that sat
abandoned next
to Grand Central Station.

21:31.690 --> 21:33.392 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Author Timothy O'Brien:

21:33.492 --> 21:37.329 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
TIMOTHY O'BRIEN, Author,
"TrumpNation": He
partnered on it with the
Pritzker family that

21:37.429 --> 21:42.268 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
owned the Hyatt hotel chain. The
Grand Hyatt
was really Donald Trump coming
onto the scene

21:42.368 --> 21:45.638 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in New York, and Donald Trump
first coming
into the public eye.

21:45.738 --> 21:53.179 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWENDA BLAIR: This was shiny,
glass, lots
of brass, stuck out in the
middle of Manhattan.

21:53.279 --> 21:59.718 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And this began his whole career
of exaggeration,
truthful hyperbole, as he calls
it, in which

21:59.818 --> 22:03.923 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
everything he does is the best,
the best of
the best, the biggest of the
biggest.

22:04.023 --> 22:09.161 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Before the project
was even completed,
The New York Times was already
branding Trump

22:09.261 --> 22:15.000 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
New York's number one real
estate promoter,
describing him in one profile as
tall, lean

22:15.100 --> 22:18.604 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and blond, and resembling Robert
Redford.

22:18.704 --> 22:24.076 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He rapidly climbed New York's
social ladder,
becoming a regular in its most
exclusive clubs,

22:24.176 --> 22:31.283 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
hobnobbing with movie stars and
models, like
Ivana Zelnickova, who he married
in 1977.

22:31.383 --> 22:37.957 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL D'ANTONIO: This was his
ambition,
to find just the right beautiful
young woman

22:38.057 --> 22:44.897 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who would fill out the picture
of the successful
man on the rise. He followed her
back to Canada,

22:44.997 --> 22:51.737 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
where she lived, and courted her
pretty avidly.
And before you know it, Ivana is
being presented

22:51.837 --> 22:58.143 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with a prenuptial agreement that
will set
the parameters for her marriage
to Donald

22:58.244 --> 23:00.246 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and her partnership with him.

23:00.346 --> 23:05.417 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: But controversy
followed Trump
wherever he went, including
public outcry

23:05.517 --> 23:11.490 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
over what was to become his
signature property,
Fifth Avenue's Trump Tower. The
old building

23:11.590 --> 23:17.997 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
facade had historic limestone
friezes that
the Metropolitan Museum of Art
wanted to preserve,

23:18.097 --> 23:19.999 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
but that would've added time to
the project.

23:20.099 --> 23:26.105 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TIMOTHY O'BRIEN: Donald is a
notoriously impatient
person, and so, in the dead of
night one night,

23:26.205 --> 23:34.847 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
he brought in a team of illegal
Polish migrant
workers, who sledgehammered the
friezes into

23:34.947 --> 23:41.020 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
dust and took them down. So,
embedded in this
triumph that is Trump Tower is
also this early

23:41.120 --> 23:45.424 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
warning sign that you have
someone who doesn't
really play well with the other
children,

23:45.524 --> 23:51.664 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and is willing to literally
pound something
into dust to get his own way.

23:51.764 --> 23:55.934 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: As banks continued
to open their
coffers with loans, he went on a
shopping

23:56.035 --> 23:57.870 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
spree.

23:57.970 --> 24:02.007 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TIMOTHY O'BRIEN: He used this
gigantic free
piggy bank, essentially, to buy
an airline,

24:02.107 --> 24:10.082 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the Trump Shuttle, to buy a
hotel, the Plaza
Hotel, to buy a football team,
the USFL Generals.

24:10.182 --> 24:14.720 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then, when he goes into
Atlantic City,
he ultimately acquires a whole
string of casinos

24:14.820 --> 24:16.622 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
there, using borrowed money as
well.

24:16.722 --> 24:21.393 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Those casinos, and
many of his
other businesses, closed one by
one, often

24:21.493 --> 24:25.431 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
amid bankruptcy claims and
unpaid debt.

24:25.531 --> 24:31.670 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
In 1989, Trump played a
controversial role
in one of the decade's most
notorious crime

24:31.770 --> 24:37.443 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
cases, when five black teenagers
were accused
of attacking a white female
jogger in Central

24:37.543 --> 24:43.248 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Park. Trump stirred what quickly
became a
boiling pot over criminal
justice and race,

24:43.349 --> 24:45.651 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
weighing on in the pages of The
New York Daily
News.

24:45.751 --> 24:50.289 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWENDA BLAIR: The case of the
Central Park
jogger, he took out a full-page
ad demanding

24:50.389 --> 24:56.695 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that whoever did this should be
sent to the
death chamber, the kids who were
arrested,

24:56.795 --> 24:59.498 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and later exonerated, by the
way.

24:59.598 --> 25:05.037 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: None of this slowed
Trump's rise.
In fact, the New York tabloids
thrived on

25:05.137 --> 25:11.610 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
his exploits, breathlessly
tracking his marriages
to Ivana and Marla Maples, his
divorces from

25:11.710 --> 25:15.114 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
both, and now, his third and
current marriage
to Melania Trump. Then, in 2004:

25:15.214 --> 25:17.049 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP (R), Presidential
Candidate:
You're fired.

25:17.149 --> 25:25.557 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: The Trump brand
found its ideal
niche, in a wildly popular
prime-time program

25:25.657 --> 25:28.394 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that celebrated everything he
had come to
represent.

25:28.494 --> 25:30.996 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP: I'm looking for
the apprentice.

25:31.096 --> 25:35.567 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Wealth, celebrity,
business success
and toughness.

25:35.667 --> 25:42.841 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWENDA BLAIR: He began "The
Apprentice," and
that turned out to be terrific
for him.

25:42.941 --> 25:49.715 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It let him be in American living
rooms every
week being the boss, being the
guy in charge,

25:49.815 --> 25:55.954 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
being the guy who hires people
and fires people.
When he first started that, was
he thinking,

25:56.054 --> 26:02.327 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
aha, straight off to the White
House? We can't
say. But, certainly, 10 years
in, that whole

26:02.428 --> 26:09.701 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
decade of people seeing him as
the boss, as
the CEO, has certainly made the
idea of his

26:09.802 --> 26:12.304 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
moving into the Oval Office seem
a matter
of course.

26:12.404 --> 26:17.943 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: From the corner
office to the
Oval Office suddenly didn't seem
that far

26:18.043 --> 26:19.945 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
a leap.

26:20.045 --> 26:27.519 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And part of a
fascinating series
of looks at the life of Donald
Trump.

26:27.619 --> 26:31.623 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Happening right now on the
convention floor,
the delegates are taking the
roll call state

26:31.723 --> 26:36.428 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
by state, casting their votes to
formally
nominate Donald Trump as the
Republican candidate

26:36.528 --> 26:37.329 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
for president.

26:37.429 --> 26:39.898 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Our Lisa Desjardins is down
there.

26:39.998 --> 26:45.504 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Lisa, we heard a few mild boos a
minute ago.
What was that all about?

26:45.604 --> 26:48.607 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: That's right.
What those boos are, Judy and
Gwen, are the
cracks in the Republican surface
coming to

26:48.707 --> 26:54.313 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
bear. Some of these states have
divided delegations,
Judy and Gwen. And some of them
are voting

26:54.413 --> 26:56.515 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
not majority for Trump.

26:56.615 --> 27:02.621 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Other delegations say they're
not able to
cast their votes the way they
want. You might

27:02.721 --> 27:07.693 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have a delegation where the
primary went overwhelmingly
for Donald Trump, but a delegate
in their

27:07.793 --> 27:11.730 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
own heart says, I don't want
support Donald
Trump, and they're trying to
vote a different

27:11.830 --> 27:13.599 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
way.

27:13.699 --> 27:16.768 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So that fracture is coming to
surface, as
some of these delegates are
trying to object

27:16.869 --> 27:21.406 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to the way this roll call is
being handled.
I will also say, even though
those boos were

27:21.507 --> 27:24.977 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
allowed, it's a minority so far
of the delegates,
but it's very significant.

27:25.077 --> 27:30.115 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: All right, Lisa,
I was reading
a little bit of the noise from
Ohio and a

27:30.215 --> 27:34.520 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
little bit from Colorado. We can
explore that
as the night goes on.

27:34.620 --> 27:39.625 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, right now, we want to bring
in our regulars
who are joining us every night
here at the

27:39.725 --> 27:41.426 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
