became a circular
firing squad. This is the thing
that David

29:31.970 --> 29:33.805 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
is talking about.

29:33.905 --> 29:35.807 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In professional campaigns, this
is not supposed
to happen. So it is one more
example of a

29:35.907 --> 29:42.514 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
campaign that is yet to get on
message. They're
going to get their take two on
unity tonight,

29:42.614 --> 29:44.316 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
but they still have not nailed
that down.

29:44.416 --> 29:46.318 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Mark, how do you
see this?

29:46.418 --> 29:50.822 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: Well, what happens
at conventions,
historically, Republican and
Democratic, nobody

29:50.922 --> 29:55.394 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
speaks a word that hasn't been
vetted and
hasn't been re-vetted.

29:55.494 --> 30:00.465 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It isn't spontaneous. You don't
get up there
and chat. This should have been,
and it wasn't.

30:00.565 --> 30:06.038 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And this was the introduction of
the candidate's
wife, who is not a public
person, who made

30:06.138 --> 30:12.778 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a positive contribution, who was
quite appealing.
And it turns out that she's --
and said she

30:12.878 --> 30:14.980 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
had written the speech herself.

30:15.080 --> 30:21.720 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it turns out that large
segments and large
